00:02:50.650 --> 00:02:53.050
And I thought law school
would be a great aspiration,

00:02:53.050 --> 00:02:56.154
but it was a bit of a lark, quite frankly,

00:02:56.154 --> 00:02:58.330
to apply to law school at the time.

00:02:58.330 --> 00:03:01.600
- And, going back to
your earlier education,

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:06.490
did you have mentors that
really pushed you along

00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:09.190
with the importance of education

00:03:09.190 --> 00:03:10.610
in the way your parents had?

00:03:10.610 --> 00:03:13.730
- Yes, I had a number of
mentors at Long Beach State.

00:03:13.730 --> 00:03:16.980
Now, again, I wouldn't
diminish them by saying

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:18.850
that they didn't contribute a lot

00:03:18.850 --> 00:03:20.720
to my development of my ideas.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:22.157
I wouldn't look back and say,

00:03:22.157 --> 00:03:23.599
"Oh, that professor or this professor

00:03:23.599 --> 00:03:25.840
really gave me a way of shaping

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:27.300
my looking at the world."

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:29.950
But, on the other hand,
they encouraged me greatly

00:03:29.950 --> 00:03:34.310
to aspire to go to get
additional education.

00:03:34.310 --> 00:03:36.330
And so it was really the
confidence that I built

00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:37.900
from my time at Long Beach State

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:40.707
that gave me the confidence that

00:03:40.707 --> 00:03:43.910
I knew that I could really thrive

00:03:43.910 --> 00:03:46.475
in a graduate school,
law school environment.

00:03:46.475 --> 00:03:48.080
- [Harry] And where did
you go to law school?

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:49.913
- I went to law school
at Harvard Law School.

00:03:49.913 --> 00:03:53.490
- And, at Harvard, what attracted you

00:03:53.490 --> 00:03:55.950
in the subfields of law?

00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:59.950
- Well, so, I loved law school, I confess,

00:03:59.950 --> 00:04:01.480
and particularly my first year,

00:04:01.480 --> 00:04:03.770
which, in law school,
is a three year program

00:04:03.770 --> 00:04:05.724
is really your core year.

00:04:05.724 --> 00:04:09.830
Subjects that I studied
and we studied at Harvard

00:04:09.830 --> 00:04:12.150
were very much like the
subjects that law students

00:04:12.150 --> 00:04:13.410
would study 100 years ago.

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:14.750
It was really a core knowledge.

00:04:14.750 --> 00:04:17.219
So my first year was really
devoted to developing,

00:04:17.219 --> 00:04:20.470
really, a background
and a base of knowledge

00:04:20.470 --> 00:04:21.330
and way of thinking.

00:04:21.330 --> 00:04:23.950
What we sometimes call
thinking like a lawyer.

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:26.170
It was really only when I got near the end

00:04:26.170 --> 00:04:27.147
of my law school career

00:04:27.147 --> 00:04:29.180
and was taking more elective subjects

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:31.640
and working with some
terrific faculty members that

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:32.880
I really started to develop

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:35.520
and nurture my interest in public law.

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:37.970
Which, in a nutshell, is
really about the relationship

00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:39.380
between law and the government.

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:41.040
About governance in the United States.

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:43.130
And so the courses that I took,

00:04:43.130 --> 00:04:45.420
papers that I was doing,
my work on the Law Review

00:04:45.420 --> 00:04:48.552
really kind of gelled to
develop my intellectual

00:04:48.552 --> 00:04:50.293
and academic interest in law.

00:04:52.706 --> 00:04:55.090
- Your interests came to be defined

00:04:55.090 --> 00:04:59.606
and the research you later
pursued sort of emphasized

00:04:59.606 --> 00:05:03.480
the dynamic of federalism on the one hand,

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:06.800
the relationship of local
government and state government,

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:10.420
but also the way it's embedded
in the politics of the time.

00:05:10.420 --> 00:05:12.020
- Well, you put it very well and

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:15.220
would that I had such a clearly defined

00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:16.400
research agenda in law school.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:17.460
I certainly didn't.

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:18.293
But certainly...

00:05:18.293 --> 00:05:19.290
And that came later.

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:22.270
But certainly that describes very well

00:05:22.270 --> 00:05:24.730
what I was mostly taken with
when I was in law school.

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:25.563
It interested me.

00:05:25.563 --> 00:05:28.675
So I did what is essentially
my master's thesis.

00:05:28.675 --> 00:05:30.910
What they call the third year paper.

00:05:30.910 --> 00:05:33.340
On federalism in the Republican tradition.

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:35.480
And so, some of the themes
that you just mentioned.

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:36.780
And really about the relationship

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:38.510
among structures of government

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:41.590
and national, state, and local governments

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:44.350
and just really how we govern
ourselves in a free society

00:05:44.350 --> 00:05:47.270
really, again, grew out of
my intellectual interest.

00:05:47.270 --> 00:05:50.440
When I look back, by the way,
on what I wrote in law school,

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:53.430
it's remarkably callow
and naive, I have to say.

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:55.630
But, really, the germs of what

00:05:55.630 --> 00:05:58.380
became my sort of academic projects

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:00.930
when I joined the faculty here.

00:06:00.930 --> 00:06:03.670
- And this must be a fertile time

00:06:03.670 --> 00:06:05.400
for that kind of research,

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:08.700
because the balance
seems to be tipping away

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:12.090
from the central government
and back to the states.

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:13.290
Is that a fair assessment?

00:06:13.290 --> 00:06:14.910
- It's an absolutely fair assessment.

00:06:14.910 --> 00:06:16.780
When I was coming out of law school

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:18.970
and, really, was beginning
my academic career,

00:06:18.970 --> 00:06:21.660
on the one hand, it was
then a fertile time,

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:23.210
because many of these issues, of course,

00:06:23.210 --> 00:06:25.370
were very prominent in American politics.

00:06:25.370 --> 00:06:26.740
On the other hand, they
weren't particularly

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:28.840
fertile in American law.

00:06:28.840 --> 00:06:30.260
To make a long story short,

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:31.667
the United States Supreme Court

00:06:31.667 --> 00:06:33.750
had mostly absented themselves,

00:06:33.750 --> 00:06:35.330
really, ever since the New Deal,

00:06:35.330 --> 00:06:37.720
from major disputes
involving the relationship

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:40.020
between the state and
national governments.

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:41.310
You could count on one hand

00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:43.470
the number of blockbuster
Supreme Court decisions

00:06:43.470 --> 00:06:44.303
on that topic.

00:06:44.303 --> 00:06:46.310
And, moreover, local government law,

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:48.470
while very important to a handful

00:06:48.470 --> 00:06:49.950
of distinguished political scientists,

00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:52.000
including some at this
wonderful university,

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:53.966
was not something that was
high on the priority list

00:06:53.966 --> 00:06:55.500
of academics.

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:57.160
In fact, if I could tell
you just a short story,

00:06:57.160 --> 00:06:59.620
when I came to the dean of this law school

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:02.420
when I was a pre-tenured faculty member,

00:07:02.420 --> 00:07:04.070
I said I really wanted to teach a course

00:07:04.070 --> 00:07:05.450
in state and local government law.

00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:06.797
And he sort of looked at me and said,

00:07:06.797 --> 00:07:09.170
"You know, we don't do that
sort of thing here at Berkeley.

00:07:09.170 --> 00:07:11.016
We're a national law school.

00:07:11.016 --> 00:07:11.849
And you might want to leave that

00:07:11.849 --> 00:07:13.030
until after you get tenure."

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:15.350
That was sort of the
status of that subject

00:07:15.350 --> 00:07:18.270
in American law schools when
I began my academic career.

00:07:18.270 --> 00:07:20.910
- And what drew you to the subject?

00:07:20.910 --> 00:07:22.830
Was it anything in your background?

00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:27.020
Or was it just you saw
it as a fallow field?

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:28.670
- You know, it was really the latter.

00:07:28.670 --> 00:07:32.118
As I started to really bear down

00:07:32.118 --> 00:07:34.840
on very important issues of governance,

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:35.680
read the literature,

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:39.130
and look at what was going on in the world

00:07:39.130 --> 00:07:39.963
in which I was living.

00:07:39.963 --> 00:07:41.780
Particularly in a place like California.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:42.990
In Northern California.

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:45.972
I always came back to the phenomenon of

00:07:45.972 --> 00:07:48.490
of state and local governments.

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:50.739
And particularly how
important and critical

00:07:50.739 --> 00:07:53.350
were issues of governance
at the local level.

00:07:53.350 --> 00:07:55.730
There was, as you probably recall,

00:07:55.730 --> 00:07:57.170
quite a lot of conversation about

00:07:57.170 --> 00:07:58.870
regionalism and regional governance.

00:07:58.870 --> 00:08:00.300
Particularly in this part of the world

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:01.740
where you have so many counties

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:03.930
sort of engaged and colliding in issues.

00:08:03.930 --> 00:08:07.710
There were so many
fertile topics of study.

00:08:07.710 --> 00:08:10.780
But, at the same time, not
that many law professors.

00:08:10.780 --> 00:08:12.500
Not that many public law scholars

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:15.412
who are really, really looking closely at

00:08:15.412 --> 00:08:18.310
issues of state governance
and local governance.

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:21.690
There was a sense that there's
not a lot in it for them.

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:23.970
And none of us really
wanted to be specialists

00:08:23.970 --> 00:08:26.680
in, say, California law
or Massachusetts law.

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:30.718
So, I saw this area as an
area of enormous interest

00:08:30.718 --> 00:08:34.150
and quite a lot of fertile topics.

00:08:34.150 --> 00:08:36.360
- And, since you were in law school,

00:08:36.360 --> 00:08:38.870
the time has come for that agenda,

00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:41.817
really, in a very pronounced way.

00:08:41.817 --> 00:08:45.340
As we see, for example, with Obamacare

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:48.300
where all the arguments are about

00:08:48.300 --> 00:08:50.343
the relationship to the state,

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:55.180
for example with the
regard to the exchanges,

00:08:55.180 --> 00:08:57.770
and whether there should
be national exchanges

00:08:57.770 --> 00:08:59.350
if there are no state exchanges.

00:08:59.350 --> 00:09:00.490
- Well, there's no question about that.

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:01.730
I mentioned, a moment ago,

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:04.790
that it wasn't, when I
began my academic career,

00:09:04.790 --> 00:09:06.950
an extremely active time

00:09:06.950 --> 00:09:10.580
in the adjudication and the
judicial process in federalism.

00:09:10.580 --> 00:09:11.880
Well, that changed quite a bit.

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:14.240
It really changed, in large part,

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:17.020
due to the innovations of the
so-called Rehnquist court.

00:09:17.020 --> 00:09:19.620
So, there was, over the
past, really, two decades,

00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:22.920
a greater amount of attention

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:24.180
on the part of the federal courts,

00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:25.610
particularly the Supreme Court,

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:26.890
on issues of federalism.

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:27.723
At the same time...

00:09:27.723 --> 00:09:29.030
And you mentioned Obamacare.

00:09:29.030 --> 00:09:32.550
The last three or four
presidential administrations

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:35.690
have brought a number of just
fascinating, interesting,

00:09:35.690 --> 00:09:38.830
novel experiments with
regard to the relationship

00:09:38.830 --> 00:09:40.860
among the state and federal government.

00:09:40.860 --> 00:09:42.650
But also with regard to the relationship

00:09:42.650 --> 00:09:44.680
between Congress and the presidency.

00:09:44.680 --> 00:09:46.238
So you have two fascinating

00:09:46.238 --> 00:09:48.890
sort of clusters of activities colliding.

00:09:48.890 --> 00:09:52.620
The greater innovation
and work done in the

00:09:52.620 --> 00:09:54.840
political branches, in
the political process.

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:57.060
But also a greater amount of attention

00:09:57.060 --> 00:09:58.370
on the part of the Supreme Court

00:09:58.370 --> 00:09:59.850
in these particular issues.

00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:04.010
- Did your background in
political science or whatever,

00:10:04.010 --> 00:10:06.820
a continuing interest you have in politics

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:09.430
inform your legal research?

00:10:09.430 --> 00:10:10.970
- You know, the answer is yes.

00:10:10.970 --> 00:10:13.340
But in a little incongruous way.

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:15.852
So, again, my own experience in college

00:10:15.852 --> 00:10:17.590
is how I've described it.

00:10:17.590 --> 00:10:18.574
My experience in law school

00:10:18.574 --> 00:10:23.500
is as a hard-working law student,

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:26.840
but it really began when
I began my academic career

00:10:26.840 --> 00:10:27.930
here at Berkeley.

00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:31.330
And I had the wonderful opportunity

00:10:31.330 --> 00:10:35.190
to learn from and study
with a number of colleagues.

00:10:35.190 --> 00:10:37.960
Both within the law
school here at Boalt Hall,

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:41.840
but also a little more indirectly

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:44.920
with some terrific political scientists.

00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:46.490
The role, just for example,

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:48.950
of the Institute of Governmental
Studies here at Berkeley

00:10:48.950 --> 00:10:50.269
was very important on me.

00:10:50.269 --> 00:10:52.952
Unlike law professors these days

00:10:52.952 --> 00:10:55.436
who tend to come to law teaching careers

00:10:55.436 --> 00:10:57.170
with another advanced degree.

00:10:57.170 --> 00:11:00.270
That's, by far, the most
common professional.

00:11:00.270 --> 00:11:01.240
I didn't.

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:03.730
So, I came here, in some sense,

00:11:03.730 --> 00:11:05.030
not being excessively humble,

00:11:05.030 --> 00:11:06.230
with no particular business

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:09.150
being a tenure-track faculty member.

00:11:09.150 --> 00:11:10.800
I didn't have another graduate degree.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:12.540
So much of my education was,

00:11:12.540 --> 00:11:14.480
as they say, on-the-job training.

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:16.440
So my first few years here at Berkeley

00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:19.280
really developed a very strong interest in

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:22.220
and I think a lot of training
in political science,

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:24.820
some amount of political
theory, economics.

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:28.970
That really helped
burnish my academic skills

00:11:28.970 --> 00:11:31.680
- And so, in a way, the challenges

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:33.656
you confronted as an individual

00:11:33.656 --> 00:11:37.821
are comparable to the
challenges you confront

00:11:37.821 --> 00:11:42.821
as a law school dean in
rethinking law school curriculum.

00:11:43.270 --> 00:11:44.650
- You know, I hadn't really
thought about it that way,

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:47.040
but I find that quite insightful.

00:11:47.040 --> 00:11:49.360
You know, I wouldn't have
thought about that at the time

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:51.570
as I began my administrative career,

00:11:51.570 --> 00:11:55.928
but, yes, in short, I think I brought

00:11:55.928 --> 00:11:58.130
both my training and my perspectives

00:11:58.130 --> 00:12:01.937
as an on-the-job trainer in these

00:12:01.937 --> 00:12:03.603
to my administrative career.

